{
  "texts": [
    "The system provides hints and creates suspicion, but it is at the officer's discretion to decide whether or not to take action (at least formally).",
    "91 Regarding the AI Act, provided that the definition of AI in Article 3 is fulfilled, automated suspicion systems are high-risk when assessing the risk of offending, security risks, risks of irregular immigration, or health risks (Annex III 7.b).",
    "Automated suspicion raises several issues that threaten fundamental rights, including the right to non-discrimination and private life.",
    "First, when the triaging system flags a case, humans are justified in taking follow-up actions based on an automated classification.",
    "However, how the system generates such classifications is often unclear."
  ]
}